Our Sunday Visitor Records

Guide

University of Notre Dame Archives

2014

Creator: Our Sunday Visitor
Title: Our Sunday Visitor Records
Dates: 1912-2016
Extent: 47 linear feet.
Language: English.
Identification: OSV

Administrative Information

Related Material

Preferred Citation

Our Sunday Visitor Records (OSV), University of Notre Dame Archives (UNDA), Notre Dame, IN 46556

Return to the Table of Contents

Background

Catholic newspaper with national circulation; files of Francis A. (Bill) Fink (1907- ), nephew of OSV founder Bishop John Noll, who served on the staff of OSV (1930-1971) as managing editor and publisher.

Return to the Table of Contents

Scope and Content

Correspondence concerning OSV publications and copies of the publications themselves; OSV minutes and communications, 1968-1971; OSV circulation and financial records, 1950s-1971; minutes of OSV staff meetings, 1961-1967; correspondence and contracts with Teamsters Union and Typographical Union; appointment book, 1965; correspondence and transcripts of recipients of Archbishop Noll Scholarships, 1955-1971; records relating to OSV college grants, 1950s-1970s; reproduction of Catholic Telegram and Advocate 11 October 1851 and OSV 5 May 1912; photographs; periodicals, pamphlets and other printed material, 1912-2016.

Return to the Table of Contents

GOSV 5/32 Colorful and inspirational was the procession in St. Boniface Church preceding Midnight Mass. Amid only the glow of Cathedral Candles at the Altar and along the walls of the Church with the flood lights casting reflections on the Crib, the formation extended down the main aisle and around the Church led by boys from the 5th, 6th, and 7th grades. Joanne McCaw as Queen, carrying the Infant Jesus, was attended by four eighth-grade girls, Beth McKay, Peggy Laws, Sharen Roark and Carol Spitznagle, wearing gowns of pale blue taffeta and carrying bouquets of red roses which they placed within the Crib. Father Laurian Rausch, O.F.M., Celebrant, Fr. Casper Rausch, Sub-Deacon, Father Niles Kraft, Deacon, and Father James Fitzpatrick, Master of Ceremonies recited the prayers at the crib. [Our Sunday Visitor, LaFayette Edition, 1/4/1959 issue] 1959/1224

GOSV 5/38 St. Richard's Catholic church, Richfield, Minn., is the scene of one of the special monthly Masses held throughout the Minneapolis-St. Paul area for shut-ins. Many of the immobilized parishioners had not been in church for as long as 10 to 30 years before the project was started by volunteer church workers. They transport the handicapped to and from their homes for the services. Shown celebrated the Mass is Father Alfred C. Longley of Richfield. [Our Sunday Visitor, LaFayette Edition, 1/4/1959 issue] 1958-1959
